  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency response to the newly arrived IDPs and hosting communities in Maaret Masrin and Armanaz communities (Idleb governorate) through provision of emergency shelter repairs.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project is designed to respond for the need of enhancing access to safe and adequate shelter for the newly arrived IDPs in two communities ( Maaret Temsrin, Armanaz).


BINAA will provide shelter light repairs at an average of $290 for 960 HHs (5760 individuals) (1235 men, 1300 women, 1580 boys, and 1645 girls) (200 in Armanaz community and 760 in Maaret Tamsrin community). The repair works will enable the target communities to use local materials and work through local contractors to improve their living conditions, fostering a sense of ownership, responsibility, and resilience while supporting local markets.
Beneficiaries numbers for the shelter units rehabilitation calculated based on average number of HH members of 6 persons.

Shelter repair beneficiaries will be newly displaced IDPs and host community households living in an inadequate shelter that does not meet minimum SPHERE minimum standards for square meters of covered living space per person and has inadequate privacy or protection from the elements, settlement planning and WASH facilities. We will target shelter units that have damage level falls within cluster recommendation - Grade 1 Slight. Works include provision and installation of doors and windows to close the openings to protect from the weather or to ensure privacy, provision of PVC door for the toilet and bathroom, and light repairs were needed.
The works will ensure increased privacy between male and females, host and hosted families that enhance gender sensitive response. Furthermore, for HHs with disabled persons, additional works will be included to respond to their needs by including disability friendly entrance and toilet facilities (e.g. use of a simple ramp with a handrail for using wheelchairs at the building entrance and seating provisions for toilets).

To participate in the project HHs and building owners should agree on the terms of assistance and sign a contract that allows the IDP household to stay in the build for one year for free to ensure that HLP guidance are considered and utilized. To benefit from the project, all beneficiaries should present valid HLP documents that verify the ownership of properties.</narrative>
  </description>
